With the emergence of antibiotic resistance the discovery of novel therapeutics to treat infectious diseases has taken on an unprecedented urgency and importance. Alarmingly, the discovery of novel natural products has decreased substantially in recent decades, in part because of pharmaceutical companies divesting in natural product research. This is due to the fact that some of the most productive sources for new antibiotics appear largely exhausted. Historically, one of the most valuable sources for novel antibiotics has been soil Actinobacteria in the genus Streptomyces, however, contemporary characterization of soil-derived Actinobacteria results largely in the rediscovery of known compounds. Therefore, identifying new sources of microbes that produce novel biologically active small molecules is critical for maintaining public health, as is increasing the efficiency with which we identify individual strains with high novel natural product potential. Through the efforts, largely initiated and made possible only by this NSF Microbial Observatory award, we have identified a rich, diverse, and largely untapped source of novel small molecules with therapeutic potential: Actinobacteria associated with terrestrial symbiotic systems. In collaboration with the Clardy lab, we have discovered 20 novel natural products from chemical characterization of 125 insect-associated Actinobacteria&mdash;a success rate of novel small molecule discovery significantly greater than the estimated 0.1% from traditional soil environments. Our findings further show that these insects appear to utilize the actinobacterial-derived compounds to inhibit specialized bacterial and fungal parasites/pathogens.

